The ‘trim principle’ is that the final height coordinate at point B is the minimum value among all these height coordinates induced by these tool profiles duplication. More precisely, on the current configurations in Figure 6b, the height coordinate at point B is given by
(5)zB=min{F(Bm)+zv(tBm),F(BM)+zv(tBM)}
where F(Bm) and F(BM) are the height coordinates of point B when the tool tip locates respectively at point Bm and BM, which can be acquired from the theoretical models discussed in Section 2.1; zv(t) is the vibration component at the cutting time t, which will be systematically studied in the this section; tBm and tBM are the corresponding times points when the diamond tool locates at the two points.
